Quick advice: 1. Confirm the price - they change it without notice. 2. Choose the cheap unlimited grill, not the expensive one. No meaningful difference, and they will start you with a huge amount of mandatory cheap meat anyway. 3. For Korean food, go to Star Karaoke instead, with good fried chicken, pancake, and service.  I used to frequent this place but will not visit again because of the disrespectful owner.  My friend reserved a table for 8 this May 2019 to celebrate graduation. 3 of our party did not appear on time, while the owner repeatedly asked us where they were and insisted that we call them. The owner eventually said to us, "When you come to America, you need to learn the American way - be on time." I am Chinese, and so are my friends.  Admittedly, 3 of us were quite late - by 30 minutes perhaps. But even if so,  why should this have anything to do with our national origin? During my several years of stay in the US, not a single person has lectured me to "learn the American way," with such an implication I found highly offensive: that since we are from China, we live by the inappropriate Chinese way that is inconsistent with the American social norm.  My previous visit to Masijta was not so pleasant either. There is another comment complaining Masijta making lunch price unavailable without updating the menu - the same happened to me. When my friend and I ordered, the server explained that lunch price was still available for my friend's order, but not for my order. He said the menu would be changed soon, and I said that's fine. However, when we had nearly finished, the server came again and told us that my friend wouldn't be getting the lunch price either, because that was their new price policy.  So here are my questions to the Masijta owner. First, you stopped offering lunch price without notifying customers on the menu - is this the "American way," from your understanding?  Second, my friend was charged more, while your server had clearly told us that her order was eligible for lunch price - is this the "American way," from your understanding?  To be fair, some food here is pretty good. But from next time I will go to Star Karaoke where the food is at least equally good, and I can have a much more comfortable experience.

The service at this restaurant is horrendous. I came in a group of four, and two of us wanted to grill. Although the menu specified that grills only require two people, the owner insisted we order more, saying we wouldn’t have enough and that the grill service was costly for her if customers didn’t order enough. It was wildly pushy and uncomfortable. As we expected, two orders were enough for the four of us.  Today, I ordered a meal through Grubhub for delivery. After receiving the wrong order, the owner refused to work with me to fix the situation. She kept repeating there was nothing I could do but order more food. The entire time she was also unapologetic.  The food is average at best, and rude behavior from the owner on more than one occasion makes it absolutely not worth it to go there again.

I am pretty new to Korean BBQ. So far, I have only had it at Star and once at Masijta. In both case we were a party of four that broadly bought the entire BBQ menu (or at least all the really fancy dishes on the menu). In case this makes a difference, we ate at Star late during a weekday evening (from about 8-10pm), and at Masijta during a Friday afternoon/early evening. Any reader should be aware, all I really care about is how good the food is-- price, atmosphere, service, etc. are all distant, secondary concerns for me, and right now, I'm focusing on finding the best Korean BBQ in around town (I like other Korean dishes as well, but I've found not nearly as much as the BBQ). The comparison between Star and Masijta BBQ isn't even a contest-- they aren't even playing in the same league. Star wins the battle of the BBQ hands down. The quality of the meat brought to the table was considerably better/better prepared at Star (Masijta's meats were all grisly and tough, Star's were all tender and succulent). Not only were the cuts of meat superior at Star, the presentation was far better. At Star, every bit of meat looked to have been carefully rolled/arranged on the platter in a artistic presentation, and each piece had obviously been given some TLC to ensure it was up to par. At Masijta, the meat came out in a massive gloppy pile (all the meats) with no care given to selection/preparation of the individual cuts or it's presentation. I only mention the presentation here because I think it speaks to how much/little care goes in to selecting the cuts of meat for the BBQ.  So, as far as Korean BBQ goes: Star gets 5 of 5 stars! ;) Every bit of meat was delicious! Masijta gets 2 of 5 stars. The quality of the meat wasn't even average-- it was below average. Of what was edible, it was tough and grisly. The pork cheek wasn't even edible.
